SIMPLE: impatient
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Impatient
<hw>Im*pa"tient</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧m*p⟦amac⟧"sh⟦eit⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[OE. <ets>impacient</ets>, F. <ets>impatient</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>impatiens</ets>; pref. <ets>im-</ets> not + <ets>patiens</ets>
patient. See <er>Patient</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not patient; not
bearing with composure; intolerant; uneasy; fretful; restless, because
of pain, delay, or opposition; eager for change, or for something
expected; hasty; passionate; -- often followed by <xex>at</xex>,
<xex>for</xex>, <xex>of</xex>, and <xex>under</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A violent, sudden, and <qex>impatient</qex> necessity.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fame, <qex>impatient</qex> of extremes, decays⟦br⟧
Not more by envy than excess of praise.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>impatient</qex> man will not give himself time to be
informed of the matter that lies before him.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dryden was poor and <qex>impatient</qex> of poverty.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not to be borne; unendurable.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Prompted by, or exhibiting, impatience; <as>as,
<ex>impatient</ex> speeches or replies</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Restless; uneasy; changeable; hot; eager;
fretful; intolerant; passionate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impatient</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Impatient
<hw>Im*pa"tient</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who is impatient.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impatiently</ent>⟦br⟧
